<b>To the Shareholders of Berkshire Hathaway Inc.:</b>

     Our gain in net worth during 1991 was $2.1 billion, or=20
39.6%. Over the last 27 years (that is, since present management=20
took over) our per-share book value has grown from $19 to $6,437,=20
or at a rate of 23.7% compounded annually.

     The size of our equity capital - which now totals $7.4=20
billion - makes it certain that we cannot maintain our past rate=20
of gain or, for that matter, come close to doing so. As Berkshire=20
grows, the universe of opportunities that can significantly=20
influence the company's performance constantly shrinks. When we=20
were working with capital of $20 million, an idea or business=20
producing $1 million of profit added five percentage points to=20
our return for the year. Now we need a $370 million idea (i.e.,=20
one contributing over $550 million of pre-tax profit) to achieve=20
the same result. And there are many more ways to make $1 million=20
than to make $370 million.

     Charlie Munger, Berkshire's Vice Chairman, and I have set a=20
goal of attaining a 15% average annual increase in Berkshire's=20
intrinsic value. If our growth in <i>book</i> value is to keep up with a=20
15% pace, we must earn $22 billion during the next decade. Wish=20
us luck - we'll need it.

     Our outsized gain in book value in 1991 resulted from a=20
phenomenon not apt to be repeated:  a dramatic rise in the price-
earnings ratios of Coca-Cola and Gillette. These two stocks=20
accounted for nearly $1.6 billion of our $2.1 billion growth in=20
net worth last year. When we loaded up on Coke three years ago,=20
Berkshire's net worth was $3.4 billion; now our Coke stock alone=20
is worth more than that.

     Coca-Cola and Gillette are two of the best companies in the=20
world and we expect their earnings to grow at hefty rates in the=20
years ahead. Over time, also, the value of our holdings in these=20
stocks should grow in rough proportion. Last year, however, the=20
valuations of these two companies rose far faster than their=20
earnings. In effect, we got a double-dip benefit, delivered=20
partly by the excellent earnings growth and even more so by the=20
market's reappraisal of these stocks. We believe this reappraisal=20
was warranted. But it can't recur annually:  We'll have to settle=20
for a single dip in the future.

<b>A Second Job</b>

     In 1989 when I - a happy consumer of five cans of Cherry=20
Coke daily - announced our purchase of $1 billion worth of Coca-
Cola stock, I described the move as a rather extreme example of=20
putting our money where my mouth was. On August 18 of last year,=20
when I was elected Interim Chairman of Salomon Inc, it was a=20
different story: I put my mouth where our money was.

     You've all read of the events that led to my appointment. My=20
decision to take the job carried with it an implicit but=20
important message: Berkshire's operating managers are so=20
outstanding that I knew I could materially reduce the time I was=20
spending at the company and yet remain confident that its=20
economic progress would not skip a beat. The Blumkins, the=20
Friedman family, Mike Goldberg, the Heldmans, Chuck Huggins, Stan=20
Lipsey, Ralph Schey and Frank Rooney (CEO of H.H. Brown, our=20
latest acquisition, which I will describe later) are all masters=20
of their operations and need no help from me. My job is merely to=20
treat them right and to allocate the capital they generate.=20
Neither function is impeded by my work at Salomon.

     The role that Charlie and I play in the success of our=20
operating units can be illustrated by a story about  George Mira,=20
the one-time quarterback of the University of Miami, and his=20
coach, Andy Gustafson. Playing Florida and near its goal line,=20
Mira dropped back to pass. He spotted an open receiver but found=20
his right shoulder in the unshakable grasp of a Florida=20
linebacker. The right-handed Mira thereupon switched the ball to=20
his other hand and threw the only left-handed pass of his life -=20
for a touchdown. As the crowd erupted, Gustafson calmly turned to=20
a reporter and declared: "Now that's what I call coaching."

     Given the managerial stars we have at our operating units,=20
Berkshire's performance is not affected if Charlie or I slip away=20
from time to time. You should note, however, the "interim" in my=20
Salomon title. Berkshire is my first love and one that will never=20
fade: At the Harvard Business School last year, a student asked=20
me when I planned to retire and I replied, "About five to ten=20
years after I die."

