     We also believe that investors can benefit by focusing on=20
their own look-through earnings. To calculate these, they should=20
determine the underlying earnings attributable to the shares they=20
hold in their portfolio and total these. The goal of each investor=20
should be to create a portfolio (in effect, a "company") that will=20
deliver him or her the highest possible look-through earnings a=20
decade or so from now. =20

     An approach of this kind will force the investor to think=20
about long-term business prospects rather than short-term stock=20
market prospects, a perspective likely to improve results. It's=20
true, of course, that, in the long run, the scoreboard for=20
investment decisions is market price. But prices will be determined=20
by future earnings. In investing, just as in baseball, to put runs=20
on the scoreboard one must watch the playing field, not the=20
scoreboard.

<b>A Change in Media Economics and Some Valuation Math</b>

     In last year's report, I stated my opinion that the decline in=20
the profitability of media companies reflected secular as well as=20
cyclical factors. The events of 1991 have fortified that case: The=20
economic strength of once-mighty media enterprises continues to=20
erode as retailing patterns change and advertising and=20
entertainment choices proliferate. In the business world,=20
unfortunately, the rear-view mirror is always clearer than the=20
windshield: A few years back no one linked to the media business -=20
neither lenders, owners nor financial analysts - saw the economic=20
deterioration that was in store for the industry. (But give me a=20
few years and I'll probably convince myself that I did.)

     The fact is that newspaper, television, and magazine=20
properties have begun to resemble <i>businesses</i> more than <i>franchises=
</i>=20
in their economic behavior. Let's take a quick look at the=20
characteristics separating these two classes of enterprise, keeping=20
in mind, however, that many operations fall in some middle ground=20
and can best be described as weak franchises or strong businesses.

     An economic franchise arises from a product or service that:=20
(1) is needed or desired; (2) is thought by its customers to have=20
no close substitute and; (3) is not subject to price regulation.=20
The existence of all three conditions will be demonstrated by a=20
company's ability to regularly price its product or service=20
aggressively and thereby to earn high rates of return on capital.=20
Moreover, franchises can tolerate mis-management. Inept managers=20
may diminish a franchise's profitability, but they cannot inflict=20
mortal damage.

     In contrast, "a business" earns exceptional profits only if it=20
is the low-cost operator or if supply of its product or service is=20
tight. Tightness in supply usually does not last long. With=20
superior management, a company may maintain its status as a low-
cost operator for a much longer time, but even then unceasingly=20
faces the possibility of competitive attack. And a business, unlike=20
a franchise, can be killed by poor management.

     Until recently, media properties possessed the three=20
characteristics of a franchise and consequently could both price=20
aggressively and be managed loosely. Now, however, consumers=20
looking for information and entertainment (their primary interest=20
being the latter) enjoy greatly broadened choices as to where to=20
find them. Unfortunately, demand can't expand in response to this=20
new supply: 500 million American eyeballs and a 24-hour day are all=20
that's available. The result is that competition has intensified,=20
markets have fragmented, and the media industry has lost some -=20
though far from all - of its franchise strength.

                    * * * * * * * * * * * *

     The industry's weakened franchise has an impact on its value=20
that goes far beyond the immediate effect on earnings. For an=20
understanding of this phenomenon, let's look at some much over-
simplified, but relevant, math.

     A few years ago the conventional wisdom held that a newspaper,=20
television or magazine property would forever increase its earnings=20
at 6% or so annually and would do so <i>without the employment of=20
additional capital</i>, for the reason that depreciation charges would=20
roughly match capital expenditures and working capital requirements=20
would be minor. Therefore, reported earnings (before amortization=20
of intangibles) were also freely-distributable earnings, which=20
meant that ownership of a media property could be construed as akin=20
to owning a perpetual annuity set to grow at 6% a year. Say, next,=20
that a discount rate of 10% was used to determine the present value=20
of that earnings stream. One could then calculate that it was=20
appropriate to pay a whopping $25 million for a property with=20
current after-tax earnings of $1 million. (This after-tax multiplier=20
of 25 translates to a multiplier on pre-tax earnings of about 16.)

     Now change the assumption and posit that the $1 million=20
represents "normal earning power" and that earnings will bob around=20
this figure cyclically. A "bob-around" pattern is indeed the lot of=20
most businesses, whose income stream grows only if their owners are=20
willing to commit more capital (usually in the form of retained=20
earnings). Under our revised assumption, $1 million of earnings,=20
discounted by the same 10%, translates to a $10 million valuation.=20
Thus a seemingly modest shift in assumptions reduces the property's=20
valuation to 10 times after-tax earnings (or about 6 1/2 times=20
pre-tax earnings).

     Dollars are dollars whether they are derived from the=20
operation of media properties or of steel mills. What in the past=20
caused buyers to value a dollar of earnings from media far higher=20
than a dollar from steel was that the earnings of a media property=20
were expected to constantly grow (without the business requiring=20
much additional capital), whereas steel earnings clearly fell in=20
the bob-around category. Now, however, expectations for media have=20
moved toward the bob-around model. And, as our simplified example=20
illustrates, valuations must change dramatically when expectations=20
are revised.

     We have a significant investment in media - both through our=20
direct ownership of Buffalo News and our shareholdings in The=20
Washington Post Company and Capital Cities/ABC - and the intrinsic=20
value of this investment has declined materially because of the=20
secular transformation that the industry is experiencing. (Cyclical=20
factors have also hurt our current look-through earnings, but these=20
factors do not reduce intrinsic value.) However, as our Business=20
Principles on page 2-3 note, one of the rules by which we run=20
Berkshire is that we do not sell businesses - or investee holdings=20
that we have classified as permanent - simply because we see ways=20
to use the money more advantageously elsewhere. (We did sell=20
certain other media holdings sometime back, but these were=20
relatively small.)

     The intrinsic value losses that we have suffered have been=20
moderated because the Buffalo News, under Stan Lipsey's leadership,=20
has done far better than most newspapers and because both Cap=20
Cities and Washington Post are exceptionally well-managed. In=20
particular, these companies stayed on the sidelines during the late=20
1980's period in which purchasers of media properties regularly=20
paid irrational prices. Also, the debt of both Cap Cities and=20
Washington Post is small and roughly offset by cash that they hold.=20
As a result, the shrinkage in the value of their assets has not=20
been accentuated by the effects of leverage. Among publicly-owned=20
media companies, our two investees are about the only ones=20
essentially free of debt. Most of the other companies, through a=20
combination of the aggressive acquisition policies they pursued and=20
shrinking earnings, find themselves with debt equal to five or more=20
times their current net income.

     The strong balance sheets and strong managements of Cap Cities=20
and Washington Post leave us more comfortable with these=20
investments than we would be with holdings in any other media=20
companies. Moreover, most media properties continue to have far=20
better economic characteristics than those possessed by the average=20
American business. But gone are the days of bullet-proof franchises=20
and cornucopian economics.

<b>Twenty Years in a Candy Store</b>

     We've just passed a milestone: Twenty years ago, on January 3,=20
1972, Blue Chip Stamps (then an affiliate of Berkshire and later=20
merged into it) bought control of See's Candy Shops, a West Coast=20
manufacturer and retailer of boxed-chocolates. The nominal price=20
that the sellers were asking - calculated on the 100% ownership we=20
ultimately attained - was $40 million. But the company had $10=20
million of excess cash, and therefore the true offering price was=20
$30 million. Charlie and I, not yet fully appreciative of the value=20
of an economic franchise, looked at the company's mere $7 million=20
of tangible net worth and said $25 million was as high as we would=20
go (and we meant it). Fortunately, the sellers accepted our offer.

     The sales of trading stamps by Blue Chip thereafter declined=20
from $102.5 million in 1972 to $1.2 million in 1991. But See's=20
candy sales in the same period increased from $29 million to $196=20
million. Moreover, profits at See's grew even faster than sales,=20
from $4.2 million pre-tax in 1972 to $42.4 million last year.

     For an increase in profits to be evaluated properly, it must=20
be compared with the incremental capital investment required to=20
produce it. On this score, See's has been astounding: The company=20
now operates comfortably with only $25 million of net worth, which=20
means that our beginning base of $7 million has had to be=20
supplemented by only $18 million of reinvested earnings. Meanwhile,=20
See's remaining pre-tax profits of $410 million were distributed to=20
Blue Chip/Berkshire during the 20 years for these companies to=20
deploy (after payment of taxes) in whatever way made most sense.

     In our See's purchase, Charlie and I had one important=20
insight: We saw that the business had untapped pricing power.=20
Otherwise, we were lucky twice over. First, the transaction was not=20
derailed by our dumb insistence on a $25 million price. Second, we=20
found Chuck Huggins, then See's executive vice-president, whom we=20
instantly put in charge. Both our business and personal experiences=20
with Chuck have been outstanding. One example: When the purchase=20
was made, we shook hands with Chuck on a compensation arrangement -=20
conceived in about five minutes and never reduced to a written=20
contract - that remains unchanged to this day.

     In 1991, See's sales volume, measured in dollars, matched that=20
of 1990. In pounds, however, volume was down 4%. All of that=20
slippage took place in the last two months of the year, a period=20
that normally produces more than 80% of annual profits. Despite the=20
weakness in sales, profits last year grew 7%, and our pre-tax=20
profit margin was a record 21.6%.

     Almost 80% of See's sales come from California and our=20
business clearly was hurt by the recession, which hit the state=20
with particular force late in the year. Another negative, however,=20
was the mid-year initiation in California of a sales tax of 7%-8=AB%=20
(depending on the county involved) on "snack food" that was deemed=20
applicable to our candy.

     Shareholders who are students of epistemological shadings will=20
enjoy California's classifications of "snack" and "non-snack"=20
foods:

