<b>H. H. Brown</b>

     We made a sizable acquisition in 1991 - the H. H. Brown=20
Company - and behind this business is an interesting history. In=20
1927 a 29-year-old businessman named Ray Heffernan purchased the=20
company, then located in North Brookfield, Massachusetts, for=20
$10,000 and began a 62-year career of running it. (He also found=20
time for other pursuits: At age 90 he was still joining new golf=20
clubs.) By Mr. Heffernan's retirement in early 1990 H. H. Brown had=20
three plants in the United States and one in Canada; employed close=20
to 2,000 people; and earned about $25 million annually before=20
taxes.

     Along the way, Frances Heffernan, one of Ray's daughters,=20
married Frank Rooney, who was sternly advised by Mr. Heffernan=20
before the wedding that he had better forget any ideas he might=20
have about working for his father-in-law. That was one of Mr.=20
Heffernan's few mistakes: Frank went on to become CEO of Melville=20
Shoe (now Melville Corp.). During his 23 years as boss, from 1964=20
through 1986, Melville's earnings averaged more than 20% on equity=20
and its stock (adjusted for splits) rose from $16 to $960. And a=20
few years after Frank retired, Mr. Heffernan, who had fallen ill,=20
asked him to run Brown.

     After Mr. Heffernan died late in 1990, his family decided to=20
sell the company - and here we got lucky. I had known Frank for a=20
few years but not well enough for him to think of Berkshire as a=20
possible buyer. He instead gave the assignment of selling Brown to=20
a major investment banker, which failed also to think of us. But=20
last spring Frank was playing golf in Florida with John Loomis, a=20
long-time friend of mine as well as a Berkshire shareholder, who is=20
always on the alert for something that might fit us. Hearing about=20
the impending sale of Brown, John told Frank that the company=20
should be right up Berkshire's alley, and Frank promptly gave me a=20
call. I thought right away that we would make a deal and before=20
long it was done.

     Much of my enthusiasm for this purchase came from Frank's=20
willingness to continue as CEO. Like most of our managers, he has=20
no financial need to work but does so because he loves the game and=20
likes to excel. Managers of this stripe cannot be "hired" in the=20
normal sense of the word. What we must do is provide a concert hall=20
in which business artists of this class will wish to perform.

     Brown (which, by the way, has no connection to Brown Shoe of=20
St. Louis) is the leading North American manufacturer of work shoes=20
and boots, and it has a history of earning unusually fine margins=20
on sales and assets. Shoes are a tough business - of the billion=20
pairs purchased in the United States each year, about 85% are=20
imported  - and most manufacturers in the industry do poorly. The=20
wide range of styles and sizes that producers offer causes=20
